div.div: This unit is described in the excavation database as below-floor fill or packing, but botanical remains suggest that it may have been a dehusking activity zone. The dry sieved portion of this unit is a small sample with an atypical distribution of scrap and diagnostics. About 40% of the sample is diagnostic, including caprine, Equid, and Bos fragments, although caprine fragments are most numerous. The unusual thing about the unit is not the diagnostics, which are fairly common, but the lack of scrap that makes the diagnostic percentage so high. The sample also includes two human bones and a worked bone (F12). Sheep-sized material includes long bone shaft, rib, and vertebral fragments. There is also a cow-sized long bone shaft fragment. There is not as much scrap as expected, and almost no vertebral and cranial scrap. Caprine material includes fragments from the hindlimb, feet, and skull. There is very little caprine skull material, though there are three maxillary teeth. Bos material includes one fragment from the forelimb and one from the feet. Equid material is limited to one metatarsal. There is not enough material from any species to discuss body part distribution. The bones are fragmented, but not as much as in some fill units -- the modal size is around 5 cm. The largest piece in the unit is a human femur 8 cm long. There are a few burnt bones (ca. 10%), mostly burnt at low temperatures, though there are also two calcined or partly calcined fragments. There is a little gnawing (<5%), mostly on long bone shaft fragments. There is no digested bone. The fragments are in mixed good condition, mostly surface condition three with some four. There are a few bones with heavy grey-white concretions. This unit has low integrity/coherence. There are a variety of taxa, but little from each species, there are a variety of surface conditions, and a few of the bones were affected by carnivores. This unit doesnâ€™t really look like massively broken fill; the pieces are large, there are more diagnostics than expected, and the species distribution is unusual for such a small sample. The surface condition is better than in many fill units (a low three) and the sample is not affected much by trampling or carnivores. However, this sample doesnâ€™t look deliberately placed, as the fragments are small and the sample has low integrity. Nor does it really look like a work surface, as there are too many fragments that are too large and that come from differentially valued/targeted parts of the animal. Could it be more like secondary fill than tertiary fill? The flotation sample (sample #1, >4mm, 100% sorted, flot 5973, recorded completely) is a smallish sample of primarily sheep-sized scrap with only a few pieces of pig- and hare-size material. There are also two fragments of modern-appearing rodent microfauna and a worked bone (F43). The sample is almost entirely scrap. Sheep-sized scrap includes primarily long bone shaft fragments, with some cranial, rib, and vertebral fragments. As in the dry sieve, though there is a lot of scrap in the sample, there are very few cranial, vertebral, and rib fragments. There are also pig-sized fragments of rib and vertebrae, cow-sized fragments of long bone and vert, and hare-sized fragments of long bone and rib. All diagnostics are caprine, with one or two fragments from the forelimb, hindlimb, feet, and skull, but there are too few to discuss body part distribution. Most (ca. 90%) of the fragments in the sample are quite small, <1cm. There are a few larger pieces, mostly two to three cm and then decreasing as size increases. Most notable are a long bone shaft fragment 9 cm long and a caprine scapula blade 7 cm long that may have been intact in the ground. There are very few diagnostics. A little of the bone is burnt (ca. 10%), mostly at low temperatures with a few fragments of calcined or partly calcined bone. A small amount of the bone has been trampled (ca. 5%), almost all of it very small fragments. There is a little gnawing (ca. 2%) and a little digested bone (ca. 5%). The fragments are generally in mixed good condition, mostly threes with some fours due to sun/wind, digestion, and trampling. This unit has low integrity/coherence. The fragments have a variety of depositional histories including burning, trampling, and carnivores. This unit mostly looks filly, since most of the fragments are small and there is low integrity/coherence. However, like the dry sieved sample, there is not as much trampling and carnivore working as in some fill units. This sample mirrors the dry sieved portion as well in that there are few fragments of vertebral, cranial, and rib scrap. Per LMâ€™s suggestion: Does this indicate different sorts of processing???
